data.name: lUsage.Text
data.value:
The process should be simple: 1. Choose your desired settings 2. Open your ROM 3. Click "Randomise"
The program takes as input a Majora's Mask (U) ROM (N64 version). This is currently the only supported ROM version, there are no plans for further support at this time. The ROM must be the original compressed version (32MB) in big endian format (.z64).
The output will be a 32MB compressed N64 ROM and optionally a Wii VC channel that can be installed via homebrew. ROM compression is done in parallel and will use a lot of CPU, so keep this in mind while running the program. This will be the majority of the program's run time, though it should not take very long to complete.
The program's directory should contain folders for the resources it accesses. These folders must be present or the program will likely fail. It is not recommended to modify any of the resource files.

data.name: lRules.Text
data.value:
There are currently 5 options for ruleset.
1. Casual/Glitchless This ruleset assumes no use of any glitches or major tricks/skips. It is suitable for any player.
2. Using Glitches This ruleset requires use of glitches to progress and unlock items. The most commonly required glitch will be bomb hovering, as this opens up the game the most in terms of area accessibility. Some clips will also be required, such as music box house early. It should not be required to use more complex glitches like 0th day to access items. This is essentially the same as the old randomiser rules but with improved item placement logic.
3. Vanilla Layout This mode does nothing - items will not be shuffled. However, it will still apply the other changes that have been selected. Selecting this option prevents base game changes other than initial file setup from being applied to the ROM as these are geared towards item shuffling.
4. User Logic This mode will allow the user to specify their own item logic for placing the items. Logic can be created via the logic editor under the customise menu.
5. No Logic Items are shuffled using only RNG - no rules or restrictions on item placement.

data.name: lBaseGame.Text
data.value:
Due to the save and reset system in Majora's Mask, some aspects are changed from the base game to allow item randomisation to work more smoothly. These are detailed below.
- Songs will act the same as items - Razor Sword is permanent and unbreakable - Business scrubs will not relocate to prevent locking out of trade rewards - Goron Lullaby requires only to wear Goron Mask and speak to the elder's son - Mountain Smithy acts as a shop rather than taking and upgrading your sword - requires 100 rupees on day 1 and gold dust on day 2 - Health restriction is lifted for Poe Hut and Secret Shrine - Deposit required for bank heart piece is dropped to 1000 rupees - Some items can be obtained multiple times to prevent locking of sidequests and upgrades - Fierce Deity's Mask is usable anywhere
Initial file conditions:
- Start in South Clock Town - 3 hearts, magic meter - Ocarina of Time - Song of Time - Song of Healing - Free item (Deku Mask for Vanilla mode)

data.name: lLogic.Text
data.value:
There is a logic editor provided with the program that will allow you to change the conditions for being able to access each item slot. By using this you can make adjustments from the standard logic to make the game easier or harder.
The editor is relatively straightforward. You simply click buttons to add/remove item dependencies for the selected slot, as well as selecting when that item is available and when it is needed for use.
Terminology is as follows:
Required - items that you absolutely must have to access the selected item.
Conditional - variable items or combinations of items needed for access. Items on the same line are needed together (AND) while separate lines define the branches that can be taken (OR).
As an example, let's use the Hero's Bow. To access this item, it is required to be able to enter Woodfall Temple. Woodfall Temple access would then be the required item. The conditional items could be Hookshot or Bomb Bag. These would be on separate lines under conditional items.
It's good to note that logic works recursively, so any requirements listed for accessing item X will automatically be requirements of any item that itself requires X.

data.name: lItem.Text
data.value:
The item list editor allows you to select exactly which items will be shuffled. Simply check the boxes of all items desired. The selected items will then be used for randomisation as long as the "custom item list" box is checked on the main form.
The text box at the bottom of the form will show the code for your selection, which you can copy/paste in case you want to keep the settings for another time or send to another player.

data.name: lShuffle.Text
data.value:
The program provides a selection of options for which elements should be shuffled. The items included by default are: - All main items - All masks (excl. Fierce Deity) - All trade items - All upgrades - All sidequest heart pieces - All minigame heart pieces - All chest heart pieces (excl. secret shrine) - All songs
There is also a setting provided for the user to specify their own list of items to be included in the shuffle.
Additional settings are explained below.
1. Songs Songs will be shuffled amongst themselves by default. Song of Soaring can be excluded to improve playing experience; it is often the most convenient method of getting around Termina. Songs may also be shuffled with the items, allowing songs to be found in item locations and vice versa.
2. Dungeon items Includes small keys, dungeon maps, compasses, and boss keys. These items will then be found at any location and will indicate to which dungeon they belong.
3. Shops This allows any item to be found and bought at a shop while shuffling the regular shop items into the item mix. Note that this may make items such as potions difficult to find. Shop items are always buyable as long as you have enough rupees.
4. Bottles This option only affects caught bottle contents, and these will only shuffle amongst themselves.
5. Everything else Includes all other chests and heart pieces that are not randomised by default, as well as heart containers and maps sold by Tingle. Items found on the moon are not included.
6. Gossip stones Gossip stones will give hints as to where some items may be found. Note that there is currently no logic for which hints will be provided or to make Mask of Truth easier to find when this option is selected.
7. Dungeon entrances This option will change which dungeon can be found in each of the four areas. It includes Woodfall Temple, Snowhead Temple, Great Bay Temple, and Inverted Stone Tower Temple. Stone Tower Temple is not included as it has no boss or blue warp.
8. Enemies Switches out enemies with others of a similar type. Working but not perfect - some scenes are currently excluded due to extra logic needed for proper functionality (Woodfall Temple, Ikana Graveyard, Sakon's Hideout, Inverted Stone Tower Temple).
9. BGM This shuffles the majority of the music and fanfares in the game and also swaps in some music from other games.

data.name: lGimmick.Text
data.value:
This section allows some gameplay alterations. It does not affect the item placement logic.
1. Damage mode This changes the way damage is handled. In doom mode, damage is as normal but Link will gradually lose health and die over a ~2 minute period. This only takes effect while in direct control of Link.
2. Damage effects Sets the type of damage dealt to Link. In random mode, the damage type will change every time damage is taken.
3. Movement Changes some basic movement mechanics. Item placement does not currently take this into account so note that low/high gravity could make some items significantly easier/harder to access.
4. Floor types Sets the physics for the ground Link is standing on. In random mode, this will pick random types every ~25 seconds and will also include lava (voids deku/zora) and deep sand (voids goron).

data.name: lCosmetic.Text
data.value:
This section should be quite self-explanatory.
1. Short cutscenes Reduces length of or skips cutscenes during gameplay.
2. Quick text Instantly print every text box.
3. Tunic colour Sets the colour of Link's tunic.
4. Play as Choose a character model. Selecting Adult Link alters Link's movement speeds and hitbox size to be the same as zora and changes the voice set. Note that this change can affect some gameplay elements - you cannot fit through some deku palace doorways in human form. Adult Link's model is currently incomplete and will be updated.
5. Tatl colour Select a colour scheme for Tatl.

data.name: lHow.Text
data.value:
The get item table is expanded to allow all randomised items to have a unique entry and during randomisation this table will be shuffled according to logic for the selected ruleset. The table format is slightly modified to allow for updates to certain items to work easily (mainly for dungeons and Tingle maps).
Chests and heart pieces have been assigned unique IDs from which they calculate their get item indices. This is done through the actors' variables.
Item repeatability is handled in the same way as scene switches (flags) are, allowing items to reset once per cycle or not at all depending on their function. This also provides a simple solution for modifying actor code that would usually check for items directly in the inventory.
Quite a lot of the work was done using external programs written to read and write the in-game file formats - these returned and updated lists of actors/variables, converted music data, and did the model swapping required for the play as options, for example.
